  "course_description": "A seminar or lecture series on topics of special sociological concern.",
  "course_notes": "Immigration is a hot-button issue in the news, both in the U.S. and around the world. With no shortage of myths and polemics, it can be difficult to sift fact from fiction. This course musters evidence from the social sciences to help students interrogate some of the most incendiary claims around migration, revealing the complexity of purportedly simple issues, putting to rest spurious claims, and humanizing the migrants themselves. We tackle four central questions: Why do people migrate? What happens to people after they migrate? What are the impacts of emigration on origin countries? And what effects do immigrants have on destination countries? The course is rooted in the U.S. case, but we will also explore immigration contexts around the world.",
